  "text": "Over the past few years, it has become apparent that virtually all viruses express proteins that target the host's IFN defence mechanisms. Collectively, these proteins target either the induction pathways or the mechanism of IFN action (for a review, see [CITATION_1] . Induction of IFN is initiated by extracellular or intracellular pattern recognition receptors that sense molecular patterns that indicate viral infection (Beutler et al., 2007) . In the case of positive-and negative-sense RNA viruses, dsRNA, a by-product of viral RNA replication, and 59-triphosphorylated RNA, respectively, are believed to be the most important IFN inducers [CITATION_2] . Once the extracellular or intracellular pattern recognition receptors are activated, a signal pathway is initiated that results in IFN-a/b transcription and release of IFN from infected cells. IFN then binds to the type I receptor, with the ensuing signal cascade leading to the formation of over 100 IFN-stimulated proteins that mediate the antiviral effect (Der et al., 1998) .",
